In Canvas, go to Files, In-class exercises, and download hsb.dta. The hsbdta dataset comes from the High School and Beyond survey.

data(hsb)
hsb

The variables in this dataset include:

  • schoolid - school identifier

  • mathach - a measure of mathematics achievement

  • ses - socioeconomic status based on parental education, occupation, & income

  • sector - a 0/1 variable for whether a school was public or private

1) Create a L2 variable for each schools mean ses and a L1 variable for each students deviation around their schools mean

hsb %>% 
  group_by(schoolid) %>% 
  mutate(sch_m_ses = mean(ses) ) %>% 
  center(ses, mean(ses)) %>% 
  head()

2) Estimate the following random-intercept model. Report and interpret the estimated coefficients below. Save your estimated model coefficients from the random-intercept model.

model_q2<-hsb %>% 
  group_by(schoolid) %>% 
  mutate(sch_m_ses = mean(ses) ) %>% 
  center(ses, mean(ses)) %>% 
  lmer(mathach ~ 1 + ses + sch_m_ses + (1 | schoolid), data = .)

tab_model(model_q2)

3) This model allows for schools to vary around the intercept (grand mean mathach score), but not around the slope. So while the average mathach score may vary between schools, the effect of ses on mathach is assumed to be the same across all schools. We can further assess this by examining a scatterplot of ses on mathach. For simplicity in graphing, create a dummy variable (slimit) that identifies whether a school had a schoolid value of < 1500.

hsb %>% 
  # mutate(pts = fitted(model_q3, level = 0, asList = FALSE)) %>% 
  filter(schoolid < 1500) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = ses, y = mathach)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  # geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  geom_abline(slope = 2.19 , intercept = 12.68) + 
  facet_wrap(~schoolid) +
  theme_textbook() + 
  scale_color_uchicago()

5) To allow for schools to vary around both the intercept (i.e., the grand mean mathach score) and slope (i.e., average effect of within-school ses on mathach), fit a random-coefficient model:

model_q5 <- hsb %>%
  group_by(schoolid) %>% 
  mutate(sch_m_ses = mean(ses) ) %>% 
  center(ses, mean(ses)) %>%
  ungroup() %>% 
  lmer(mathach ~ 1 + ses + sch_m_ses + (1 + ses | schoolid), data = .)

tab_model(model_q5)

Save your estimated model coefficients from the random-coefficient model.

(Hint: use the following command in Stata: estimates store rand_coef).

Construct a 95% prediction interval for the school slopes

slopes_CI <- function(estimate, variance) {
  
  ub<-estimate + (1.96*sqrt(variance))
  lb<-estimate - (1.96*sqrt(variance))
  print(paste("UB is", round(ub,3), "LB is", round(lb,3)))
}

slopes_CI(2.19, 0.69)
## [1] "UB is 3.818 LB is 0.562"

What does this prediction interval tell you?

6) We can empircally test whether or not we need to model the random slope by using a naiive likelihood-ratio test. The null hypothesis, that the variation of the slope is equal to 0, is tested against the alternative hypothesis, that the variation of the slope is greater than 0. Report the estimated p-value and interpret the results. (Hint: use the following command in Stata: lrtest rand_int rand_coef, stats)

anova(model_q4, model_q5, test = "Chisq")

7) We want to know if the association between a students ses and their math achievement, which we found varied significantly across schools, can be further predicted by their schools sector (public vs.private), as shown in the following model:

model_q7 <- hsb %>%
  group_by(schoolid) %>% 
  mutate(sch_m_ses = mean(ses) ) %>% 
  center(ses, mean(ses)) %>%
  ungroup() %>% 
  lmer(mathach ~ 1 + ses*sector + sch_m_ses + (1 + ses | schoolid), data = .)

tab_model(model_q7)
